@benhuh I'll still be looking for SaaS, to be clear. But it'll have to feel like a necessity, not a luxury. The good news is climate SaaS will have some regulatory pull around it that'll make it more must-have and less nice-to-have.

@benhuh Consolidation, probably, and de-duping (like the Slack/Teams example). Flirtations with stuff your Gen Z teams love will end (i.e. Marketplace had a brief affair with AirTable). And NEW entrants that aren't differentiated ("better" Figma/Carta/Notion etc) will struggle.
@Patticus YAY!! Please do. :) And also PHEW, was way out on that limb there.

I suspect the days of rubber-stamping anything with SaaS on it are over, or should be. We're at saturation. SaaS-turation, even. I slay me. And apparently I also slay VC sacred cows in year one, so we'll see how wrong I am in another few, that's always a possibility, too. ü§£

It's easy money for VC, and I'm not knocking software -- climate solutions NEED a software layer, and measurement, and subscription services that provide easy access to sustainability data, as just a few examples. The margins are great. But it's time to get a lot pickier, too.

And it seems clear that businesses are likely going to start trimming the fat on b2b SaaS (do you really *need* Slack when you already pay for Microsoft and Teams is built right in?). And we've flooded the zone with NEW subscription services that might never get traction at all.

Like, lazy-night deliveries from restaurants, that just got a budget cap. I'm not paying for Motor Trends just to sometimes watch Top Gear America. I quit the Farmer's Dog subscription in favor of cheaper dehydrated food. Now imagine that but at the enterprise scale ...

If I look around at the places in my life where I can trim, it's not the mortgage, or the car payment, or tutoring or food. It's the extras, and a lot of those are subscription services that make my life more convenient, but that I won't die or freeze without.

The consumer landscape often provides clues to these kinds of trends, and SaaS (subscription as a service) is headed to the same place as streaming fatigue. There are too many things to subscribe to, it's confusing, it's an increasingly huge line item, and it's OPTIONAL.

I was talking to a startup's customer the other day, and he said something that should send a chill up every SaaS investor's spine: "The question isn't whether this works or can improve our efficiency. It's whether we need ANOTHER $50,000 business software thing to sign up for."

üßµOk, so I've been an investor for a little less than a year. But I've been in the pattern recognition game for my entire life and I've got a prediction. The B2B SaaS bubble, the darling of the VC world, is going to pop badly, and maybe soon.

And obviously, once we got to zero and stayed there, there were no arrows in the quiver at all. And historically speaking, at least going back to say, the 80s, our current 3.25 is still pretty low. All that's to say that if I'm the Fed, I'm gonna push this as far as I can. 4/

There was a little flirtation with 2-2.5% in 2018 and 2019 there, but then pandemic. This has actually left the Federal Reserve pretty constrained in terms of reacting to economic pressures. If you want to stimulate growth by lowering rates, there wasn't a lot to work with 3/

But the thing is, interest rates have been low for a *very long time,* because the recovery from the 2008 collapse was so protracted and slow. We haven't been above 3% *since* 2008, in fact. 2/ https://t.co/i5LIAynDAe

So, I'm having some thoughts about interest rates. Perhaps @kairyssdal or @Neil_Irwin can weigh in. Interest rates, as we discussed many times, are the Fed's big tool to react to economic conditions. Need to stem inflation? Raise rates. Need to stimulate growth? Lower rates. 1/üßµ

Anyway it's a weird Sunday in the eye of the hurricane and I need to do the laundry now so thanks for letting me have it out, I guess. Hang in there, friends. The world will unfold on its own time.

But then again, the future isn't written, and everything is known and knowable all at the same time, and we're both tormented and blessed by it. Blessed to have all of this knowledge available and tormented by the need for more and the need for the knowledge to become action. 7/

Also, I have to be honest, it's incredibly frustrating that when we have all of human history at our fingertips and every opportunity to avoid making the same mistakes over and over again, we keep making the same mistakes over and over again. 6/

I'm also reminding myself that speed leads to mistakes, and delay can be thoroughness, not laziness or ignorance. It's difficult. I feel paralyzed with rage and grief. I feel like when nothing is happening, nothing is happening. But that's not true. The water teems. 5/

And at this moment, I'm trying to remind myself that the world will get there. The investigations will unfold. Truths will be revealed to more people every minute, every day. The things that are being clamored for, some, if not all, of those things will happen. 4/

You realize that you exist in a different timeline. You exist in the future where all the details are known, the facts are obvious, every take has already been taken like COME ON WORLD, we talked about this already, WHERE HAVE YOU BEEN. You're like Yoyo in Agents of Shield. 3/

And it gets so frustrating and painful and downright infuriating the watch the IRL world catch up. To watch investigations play out like they're supposed to, and to watch information be slowly, so agonizingly slowly, disseminated out to everyone, and not just the Very Online. 2/

The problem with Twitter is that it's basically a time machine. Or maybe it's a wormhole. It's the place where everything is known, and knowable, all at the same time. And then we (I, I mean me here) want the rest of the world to operate at this timescale. 1/
